# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1877-major-league-baseball-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1874-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1874 throughout the world.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The **1876 major league baseball season** was contested from April 22 through October 21, 1876, and saw the Chicago White Stockings as the pennant winner of the inaugural season of the National League and of Major League baseball.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Two non-NA teams would join as charter members, including the Cincinnati Reds (unrelated to the modern team) and Louisville Grays.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The 1876 schedule was formatted so that each team would play up to 10 games against each team in the league (split evenly between home and away games), for a maximum of 70 games (only fulfilled by the Boston Red Caps).
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Any game played against a team at home must be played within two months' time away, "under penalty of forfeiture." This was the only season that the National League adopted this format.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see a more regulated format, requiring teams to schedule 12 games against each team.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 22 featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Athletics of Philadelphia.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on October 21, featuring a game between the Hartford Dark Blues and Boston Red Caps.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The first doubleheader in major league history occurred on September 9 between the Cincinnati Reds and Hartford Dark Blues.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The year ended with the first postseason competition in major league history.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The contest featured the first and second-place regular season finishers.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Three tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind occurred throughout the season (though standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The Louisville Grays had three tie games.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The Hartford Dark Blues, New York Mutuals, and Philadelphia Athletics had one tie game each.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The Hartford Dark Blues would play their final game at the Hartford Ball Club Grounds on September 16 against the St.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings, relocating to Brooklyn, New York at the Union Grounds as the Brooklyn Hartfords for the start of the 1877 season.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] The **1877 Boston Red Caps season** was the seventh season of the franchise.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] Arthur Soden became the new owner of the franchise, who won their first National League pennant.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-brooklyn-hartfords-season] The Hartford Dark Blues moved to Brooklyn, New York prior to the 1877 season and were renamed as the **Brooklyn Hartfords**.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-brooklyn-hartfords-season] This was to be the Hartfords' last season, as they disbanded following the completion of their schedule.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1877 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 6th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the 2nd in the National League and the fourth at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished fifth in the National League with a record of 26–33.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] The **1877 Cincinnati Reds season** was the team's second season in the National League.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] The team finished sixth and last in the league with a record of 15–42, 25½ games behind the first place Boston Red Caps.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] After finishing dead last in the National League in the 1876 season, the Reds attempted to improve their club by signing Lip Pike, who spent the previous season with the St.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] Pike was also named the manager of the team.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds got off to another terrible start, as they had a 3–11 start to the season, and Pike stepped down as the manager.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] The team was briefly disbanded by owner Josiah Keck, and although a group of eight businessmen stepped in to rescue the franchise, some Cincinnati players had been signed by other teams in the interim, and some newspapers subsequently refused to list the Red's results.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] Bob Addy took over as player manager; however, he too saw very few wins as Cincinnati went 5–19 during his managerial stint.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] Jack Manning then finished the year as player-manager, going 7–12, as the Reds had a 15–42 record and once again finished in the National League cellar, 25.5 games behind the first place Boston Red Caps.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] Charley Jones had another solid season for the Reds, hitting .310 with two homers and a team high 36 RBI.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] Manning also had a solid year, hitting .317, as he had a team high 80 hits while tying Jones with a team high 36 RBI.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] Pike hit .298 with a team high four home runs, and added 23 RBI.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] On the mound, rookie Bobby Mitchell came up late in the season and was very impressive, leading Cincinnati with six victories and a team best 3.51 ERA in twelve games.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-louisville-grays-season] The **1877 Louisville Grays** were the victim of Major League Baseball's first gambling scandal.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-louisville-grays-season] Pitcher Jim Devlin, outfielder George Hall, utility player Al Nichols and shortstop Bill Craver were accused of throwing games at the end of the season.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-louisville-grays-season] All four were banned from baseball for life.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-louisville-grays-season] The team was unable to continue and folded after the season.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-louisville-grays-season] After a spectacular start that included a 27–13 record to begin the season, the Grays mysteriously lost seven games in a row.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-louisville-grays-season] Players bobbled the ball, seemed to slow between bases, and swung suspiciously wide.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-louisville-grays-season] The result was that the Grays lost the pennant.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The **1877 major league baseball season** was contested from April 30 through October 6, 1877, and saw the Boston Red Caps as the pennant winner of the second season of the National League.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] Over the off-season, in December 1876, two teams were formally kicked out of the league for failing to fulfill their schedules: New York Mutuals and Philadelphia Athletics, contracting the league from eight to six teams.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Hartford Dark Blue would relocate from Hartford, Connecticut to Brooklyn, New York, as the Brooklyn Hartfords.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The 1877 schedule consisted of 60 games for all six teams of the National League.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 12 games against the other five teams in the league.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season that the National League adopted the format.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The format would last only through the following season.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 30 featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Brooklyn Hartfords.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on October 6, featuring four teams.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Hartfords hosted a neutral site game.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Hartfords had two tie games.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Red Caps, Chicago White Stockings, Cincinnati Reds, and Louisville Grays had one tie game each.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Stockings would play their final game at 23rd Street Grounds on October 6 against the Louisville Grays, moving to Lakefront Park for the start of the 1878 season.
[src:1877-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Hartfords hosted a neutral site game against the Chicago White Stockings on their last home game of the season, September 22, at the site of the former National Association's New Haven Elm Citys, at the Howard Avenue Grounds in New Haven, Connecticut.
